Shopify Data Science Internship Challenge

library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(plyr)

=====

Question 1:

On Shopify, we have exactly 100 sneaker shops, and each of these shops sells only one model of shoe. We want to do some analysis of the average order value (AOV). When we look at orders data over a 30 day window, we naively calculate an AOV of $3145.13. Given that we know these shops are selling sneakers, a relatively affordable item, something seems wrong with our analysis.

  1. Think about what could be going wrong with our calculation. Think about a better way to evaluate this data.
  2. What metric would you report for this dataset?
  3. What is its value?

Answer 1 :

Note: although the answers are presented here, a more detailed solution and analysis for the answers to this question is presented below.

  1. Given small sample size (5000 rows) the presence of extreme outliers can skew the mean/AOV value.
  2. Assuming that we make no modification to the original data set such as purging the outliers, then using the median value (284.00) as opposed to the mean will yield a value that is more representative of the ‘middle’ of all the order_amount per order. The median value falls within the order of magnitude for sneakers. Furthermore, even after purging the top 2% of outliers (2% of the most extreme outliers) in our data, the mean value obtained is 297.70 which is close to our median value from unpurged data (284.00).
  3. The value of the median of both the original data set and the data set purged of the top 2% of outliers are both 284.00

===

Question 2

  1. How many orders were shipped by Speedy Express in total?
SELECT COUNT(OrderID) 
FROM Orders 
LEFT JOIN Shippers ON Shippers.ShipperID = Orders.ShipperID
WHERE ShipperName = 'Speedy Express';

Answer is 54

  1. What is the last name of the employee with the most orders?
SELECT EmployeeID, COUNT(EmployeeID) 
FROM Orders 
GROUP by EmployeeID 
ORDER by COUNT(EmployeeID) DESC;

Answer is employee 4 with 40 orders

  1. What product was ordered the most by customers in Germany?
SELECT OrderDetails.ProductID, COUNT(OrderDetails.ProductID)
FROM ((Orders
INNER JOIN Customers ON Orders.CustomerID = Customers.CustomerID)
INNER JOIN OrderDetails ON Orders.OrderID = OrderDetails.OrderID)
WHERE Customers.Country = 'Germany'
GROUP by OrderDetails.ProductID
ORDER by COUNT(OrderDetails.ProductID) DESC;

Answer: The Product of id 31 has the most order (5) amongst customers from Germany

A more in depth look to question 1

Step 1: Exploratory Data Analysis

Here is an extract of our data set

data <- fread("shopify_data.csv") 
data %>% head()

Our target will be ‘order_amount’

names(data)
[1] "order_id"       "shop_id"        "user_id"        "order_amount"   "total_items"    "payment_method" "created_at"

Categorical:

names(data)[which(sapply(data, is.character))]
[1] "payment_method" "created_at"

Numeric:

names(data)[which(sapply(data, is.numeric))]
[1] "order_id"     "shop_id"      "user_id"      "order_amount" "total_items"

By quickly checking our features we see that order_id is independent to the order amount. We have numerical features shop_id, user_id, total_items and categorical features for payment_method and created_at.

data %>% dim()
[1] 5000    7

So we have a very small data set (5000 x 7). This should already raise a flag, as the presence of extreme outliers can really mess up a small sample of data.

summary(data$order_amount)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
     90     163     284    3145     390  704000 
sd(data$order_amount)
[1] 41282.54
var(data$order_amount)
[1] 1704248055

As we can see, the standard deviation and variance are off the roof (std dev at 41 282.54$), putting this into context of sneaker sales makes no sense as 41 000 $ is the price magnitude for buying a car. As expected, the mean or AOV is at 3145.00$ which is extremely high for sneakers. Given the small size of our data set (5000 rows) and a mean that seems too high, we can hypothesize on the existence of extreme outliers strongly pulling the mean upward. This is also shown by a median of 284$, a 25th percentile at 163$ and 75th precentile at 390$, which all fall under the order of magnitude one can expect for sneakers.

Let’s to have a more visual representation of our data by doing a box plot of the order_amount to illustrate potential outliers.

boxplot(data$order_amount)

We can see that our outliers are so far from 75% of our data that we see it represented as a single line as opposed to a box. A key take away from this visualization is that 75% of our data has a range (height) of a line compared to the distance between the line and the points that are outliers.

Now let’s see if the order creation data has any effect on the outliers, perhaps a glitch in the system on a certain day

boxplot(data$order_amount~data$created_at)

The outliers seem to be spread out accross different dates.

Now, let’s do the same thing by plotting the box for each shop_id

boxplot(data$order_amount~data$shop_id)

We can clearly see that a few shops contains all the extreme outliers in our data set. Furthermore, there seems to be one shop where 75% of its orders are spanned accross 0 to 70 000…

Now finally let’s apply the same thing grouping by payment_method

boxplot(data$order_amount~data$payment_method)

we can observe a slight decrease in the presence of far and extreme outliers for the orders that were paid in cash.

Boxplot with grouping by user_id should not yield any concrete insight but let’s check it out nonetheless.

boxplot(data$order_amount~data$user_id)

there is no siginificant user who overspent compared to the others.

Step 2: Analysis on order_amount and shop_id

Let’s grab a copy of our data

quantile(amount_by_shop$order_amount, .98)
   98% 
800.08

Heuristically, we have decided to use the 98th percentile as the cut-off point for determining outliers or not.

outliers <- amount_by_shop[amount_by_shop$order_amount > 801]
outliers %>% head()
outliers %>% dim()
[1] 100   2

We have cut 2% of the data, which represent 100 rows

Now let’s check the frequency by shop_id to see if there is any shop that produces more outliers and another,

As we can see, it seems that 69% of the outliers ((46 + 23)/100 outliers) are originated from orders made from 2 shops: shop_id == ‘78’ and shop_id == ‘42’

Now back to the data that is purged from the top 2% extreme outliers, we have

purged <- data[data$order_amount < 801]
summary(purged$order_amount)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
   90.0   163.0   284.0   297.7   386.0   800.0 
boxplot(purged$order_amount)

We can see that the median value has not changed, still at 284. Also, after cutting out the outliers, our mean value is very close to our median value (297.7)

Step 3: Contextualize our findings

In step 2, we have seen the effect of extreme outliers that constituted 2% of our data set and how by purging the extreme outliers, we obtained a mean value closer to the median value. Given the context of online stores selling sneakers, the adjusted-mean of 297.7 $ per order or median of 284 $ per order seems to have a good magnitude for sneaker prices which ranges in the hundred of dollars.

In step 2, we have also tried to briefly examine the circumstances of the extreme outliers and have found by visual inspection (no hypothesis testing) that 2 shops (shop_id ‘78’ and ‘42’) seems to contain 69% of the 2% of extreme outliers purged from our data set. Without more information, we can make an educated guess that these shops are some kind of wholesale or supplier whose customers are sneaker stores themselves, thus providing one possible explanation to the disproportionally huge size of order_amount made from these stores.
